[Title Block] Lead Intelligence & AI-Powered Outreach System
[Subtitle Block] Software Design Document - Internal Edition
[Normal] This document defines the final operating design for an internal lead intelligence platform. The system preserves raw intake data, normalizes and deduplicates records, builds company context, anchors all messaging in a maintained capability library, and uses AI only as a constrained drafting assistant. The intent is not to automate outreach blindly. The intent is to give the company a small, reliable, auditable, and highly controlled engine for moving from raw records to approved conversation.
[Normal] The central design choice is simple: the company's internal solutions and proof points are the primary asset, company research is the supporting context, and every outbound message is built from those two layers before it ever reaches Outlook.

[Heading 1] 1. Executive Summary
[Normal] The system is a closed-loop lead intelligence and outbound execution platform built for a single internal company environment. It exists because raw spreadsheets do not become a sales engine on their own. A spreadsheet can hold volume, but it cannot hold context, consistency, or memory. This platform closes that gap by turning imported rows into normalized entities, linking each contact to a company, attaching research and capability context, and then using AI to draft outreach that reflects what the company actually knows how to do.
[Normal] The operating intent is not to create a CRM, a marketing automation suite, or a generic campaign engine. The intent is to create a controlled intelligence-to-outreach pipeline where internal capabilities are the center of gravity. The platform should know what the company can sell, what problems it solves, what evidence it can support, and which industries or company types it is most credible with. Company research is important, but it is secondary to the capability library. The message should always start from a real service, a real proof point, and a real reason to reach out.
[Normal] The message lifecycle is deliberately strict. Data enters through batch import. It is cleaned, normalized, and deduplicated. Company records are created or updated. Research notes and internal capability items are attached. AI receives only the curated context it needs. Drafts are reviewed by a human before they are allowed to reach Outlook. Replies, bounces, and suppressions feed back into the data so the system becomes cleaner and more accurate over time. The result is a simple operating loop: raw data to qualified intent to context to message to send, with every step recorded and reviewable.
[Normal] The success measure for this system is not raw email volume. Success is the percentage of leads that can be accurately cleaned, correctly tied to a company, matched to a relevant service angle, converted into a credible draft, and sent without violating internal rules or losing traceability. In practical terms, the system should help the business use its own knowledge more consistently, reduce manual copywriting effort, improve list hygiene, and produce messages that sound like the company actually wrote them for the recipient's business context.
[Heading 2] 1.1 What the platform must do
[Normal] The platform must import large static datasets, preserve the source of every row, identify duplicates, calculate whether a record is ready for outreach, and keep company context reusable across all contacts at the same organization. It must also surface where the data is incomplete or risky, rather than hiding problems behind a polished interface. A lead should never become send-ready just because it exists in the database. It becomes send-ready only when it is clean, connected, understood, and supported by an approved outreach angle.
[Heading 2] 1.2 What the platform must not do
[Normal] The platform must not become a sprawling CRM with tasks, deals, service tickets, project plans, and unrelated operational clutter. It must not scrape the open web indiscriminately. It must not invent company capabilities that are not in the internal knowledge base. It must not send automatically without a human approval gate. It must not hide raw values or overwrite imported history. Those boundaries are not limitations; they are the reason the system stays trustworthy.
[Heading 1] 2. System Intent and Design Principles
[Heading 2] 2.1 Internal capabilities first
[Normal] The most important design rule is that the company's internal capabilities and solutions come first. The platform should treat every case study, service description, delivery approach, proof point, and approved call-to-action as a reusable asset. These assets are not attachments to the system; they are the memory of the business. When an AI draft is produced, it should be built from that memory before anything else is considered. If the system cannot find a credible internal solution angle, the right response is not to improvise. The right response is to flag the record for more research or a different service angle.
[Normal] This principle changes the way the entire product behaves. Instead of asking, "What can we say to this lead?" the system asks, "What do we know how to solve, and which part of that solution is relevant to this company?" That shift protects the company from generic outreach. It also helps the sales team repeat its best ideas without rewriting them every time. The platform becomes a knowledge amplifier rather than a content generator.
[Heading 2] 2.2 Controlled intelligence, not automation
[Normal] The platform should feel intelligent, but it should remain controlled. That means every transformation must be explainable and reviewable. Importing a lead should not silently change the meaning of the data. Duplicates should not disappear without a log. AI should not be free to invent missing facts. Sending should not happen because a workflow rule happened to fire at the wrong time. Every major action needs a visible state change and an audit trail.
[Normal] In practice, controlled intelligence means the system can assist with judgment but cannot replace judgment. AI can suggest an opening sentence based on company context. It cannot decide that a lead is safe to email if the record is suppressed. It can recommend a solution angle, but it cannot claim experience that does not exist in the capability library. It can produce a draft, but the draft stays in review until a human approves it. The system is therefore more like a disciplined assistant than an autonomous agent.
[Heading 2] 2.3 One source of truth, one company context
[Normal] Every contact belongs to a company, and every company can have one shared context record. That structure prevents duplicated research and inconsistent messaging. When three people from the same company are imported, the system should not create three separate versions of the same company story. It should create one company anchor, one research card, and one evolving set of notes that all contacts can reuse. This makes the platform simpler to maintain and more useful to the people writing outreach.
[Normal] The same rule applies to raw data and edited data. The imported value is preserved. The cleaned value is preserved. The user-edited value is preserved. The system should never destroy its own history just because a user improves a field. That history is what lets the team trust the platform later, especially when a batch was messy or the source file was inconsistent.
[Heading 2] 2.4 Simple workflows, low cognitive load
[Normal] The interface should not make the user think like an admin of a software platform. It should make the user feel like they are working through a very small, very clear sequence: import, clean, review, research, draft, approve, send, and learn from the results. Anything that does not support that sequence should be compressed, hidden behind settings, or removed. A good internal tool does not expose all of its machinery in the main workflow. It exposes only the decisions that matter.
[Normal] This is why the design should prefer a narrow number of screens, a narrow number of lead states, and a narrow number of action buttons. The user should be able to understand what will happen before they click it. If the system needs a complex rule, that rule should live in the background. If the system needs a complex explanation, that explanation should appear in the audit trail or the detail view, not in the default path.
[Heading 1] 3. Roles and Permissions
[Heading 2] 3.1 Administrator
[Normal] The administrator is responsible for the structural settings of the platform. This role manages import templates, column mappings, user access, suppression rules, capability library structure, AI settings, send limits, and integration credentials. The administrator can also revise scoring rules, archive old batches, restore records, and control any global kill switch such as pause-all-sends. Because the system is internal, the admin role should be powerful but still accountable through audit logs.
[Heading 2] 3.2 Reviewer
[Normal] The reviewer is the quality gatekeeper. This role handles fuzzy duplicates, risky email records, uncertain company matches, and AI drafts that need closer inspection. The reviewer does not need to manage infrastructure, but they do need visibility into raw values, cleaned values, source history, and the reason a record was flagged. Their job is to protect data quality and message quality at the point where the system would otherwise be tempted to guess.
[Heading 2] 3.3 Sender
[Normal] The sender is the person or role allowed to approve drafts and release them into Outlook. The sender should see the queue, the send schedule, the daily cap, and the status of each outbound item. The sender does not need to manage the entire data model. They need a fast, confident way to review a draft, edit it if necessary, and move it forward. The platform should optimize this role for speed without allowing the sending step to bypass policy.
[Heading 2] 3.4 Viewer
[Normal] The viewer can search, inspect, and learn from the system without changing core settings. This role is useful for managers, sales leadership, and other internal stakeholders who need visibility into the lead base, the quality of the data, the state of the queue, and the performance of the outreach process. A viewer should not be able to alter suppression rules, edit capability claims, or send email.
[Heading 2] 3.5 Permission philosophy
[Normal] Permissions should be role-based but simple. The system should not become a labyrinth of per-field permissions unless there is a real internal need. The main thing is that anything that can affect compliance, deliverability, or company positioning must be restricted and logged. Editing a contact note is less sensitive than changing the approval text in the capability library. Adjusting a lead status is less sensitive than removing a suppression entry. The permission model should reflect those differences without overwhelming the user.
[Heading 1] 4. System Architecture and Runtime Model
[Heading 2] 4.1 High-level layers
[Normal] The application should be understood as five connected layers. The first layer is ingestion, where files enter the system and are staged. The second layer is data processing, where fields are normalized, duplicates are detected, and rows are classified. The third layer is intelligence, where company context and capability knowledge are assembled. The fourth layer is generation and execution, where AI produces drafts and Outlook handles approved mail. The fifth layer is feedback, where replies, bounces, suppressions, and health refresh jobs keep the data alive.
[Normal] These layers should be loosely coupled so that one part can fail without destroying the entire platform. A problem in AI drafting should not block batch import. A temporary issue in Outlook should not erase cleaned company records. A duplicate review queue should not stop a weekly email health run. The architecture should therefore favor clear interfaces, job queues, and explicit state transitions over hidden cross-dependencies.
[Heading 2] 4.2 Runtime behavior
[Normal] The runtime should be batch-driven and idempotent. When a file is uploaded, the system should be able to reprocess the same batch without creating duplicate records. When a record is edited, the deduplication process should be able to run again and return the same logical answer. When a message is prepared, the output should be reproducible from the same inputs, subject to the current version of the capability library and research card. This reduces operational surprises and makes debugging possible.
[Normal] Because the intended dataset is large, the backend should process rows in chunks and push expensive work into background workers. Heavy operations such as AI generation, email health refresh, and duplicate rechecks should not block the user interface. The user should see progress, status, and queue counts while the system continues working in the background. That balance keeps the tool responsive without pretending that 100,000 rows can be treated like a small list.
[Heading 2] 4.3 Storage model
[Normal] The system should maintain separate storage for raw files, staged rows, master records, capability assets, generated drafts, outbound logs, replies, and audit events. Raw imports are preserved as evidence. Master records hold the current truth. Staged rows hold exceptions and intermediate work. Drafts hold AI output and human edits. Logs hold delivery events. Audit records hold who changed what and when. This separation is important because it allows the team to recover from mistakes, analyze problems, and trace a message back to the source input.
[Heading 2] 4.4 Integration model
[Normal] The only mandatory external integration is Outlook for sending and reply tracking. Any company research connected to the system should be curated and limited to company-level and industry-level context. The platform should not depend on a patchwork of unrelated tools. If a public source is used, it should be chosen because it helps the company understand the prospect's context and can be stored as a short, reviewable note. The architecture should always prefer a compact internal record over a sprawling external dependency graph.
